Ok, we won't get to *all* those questions, but we'll have a shared doc where you all can add your own answers and together we'll create a rich resource for all of us 💚

Last question:

What does someone need to know or skills they need to have to start maintaining a package?
How do you decide to submit to a centralized repository like CRAN or @Bioconductor? Peer review like JOSS or rOpenSci? Stay only on GitHub?
What considerations are different for a public vs. an organization's internal package?
What does the process of changing maintainers look like? What sets up this transition for success?
What do you consider when other packages depend on *your* work?
What considerations go into decisions around dependency management? APIs that change?

What is a path for new contributors to R packages? How can healthy norms be passed on?

And what should someone do if they want to start help maintain one of *your* packages?
How do you manage issues / feature requests? What workflows do you use?
How do you encourage user feedback and/or manage a firehose of user feedback or requests for help?
What does it mean to  “maintain an R package”?

Building community remotely since 2011. Hoping to bring you some calm amid the storm.

Join us online tomorrow (Wed). Five smart and generous folk in Q & A about maintaining an R package.

Other rOpenSci community activities continue. We express our continued great appreciation for the work of our authors and reviewers.
In this period new submissions will not be handled, nor new reviewers assigned. Reviews and responses to reviews will be handled on a ‘best effort’ basis, but no follow-up reminders will be sent.

⚠️ rOpenSci is pausing new submissions for software peer review for 30 days (possibly longer) in the interest of reducing load on reviewers and editors as we manage the COVID-19 crisis. 

Stay healthy and take care of one other
